name: Arugula
description: Arugula is a fast-growing, cool-season leafy green that adds a tangy, mustard-like flavor to salads.

name: Basil
description: Basil is a warm-weather, fragrant herb that tastes great in many dishes—including the beloved homemade pesto!

name: Beets
description: Beets grow easily and you won’t have to wait long to harvest their tasty roots. You can eat their green tops, too.

name: Bell Peppers
description: Peppers are a warm-season crop and come in a variety of colors, shapes, and sizes. Add one to your salad!

name: Broccoli
description: The deliciously tender spears of garden-grown broccoli are also incredibly good for you—the “crown jewel of nutrition.”

name: Cabbage
description: Cabbage is a cool-season leafy vegetable — which is packed with vitamins — suited to both spring and fall!

name: Cantaloupe
description: Cantaloupes are a delicious, heat-loving melon with a relatively long growing season. Sweet and delicious!

name: Carrots
description: Everyone enjoys a sweet, crunchy carrot! Carrots are an excellent source of vitamin A. And rabbits love them.

name: Cauliflower
description: An annual plant in the Brassica family, cauliflower's edible white flesh is extremely healthy and considered a 'superfood.'

name: Celery
description: Not only is garden celery better-tasting than store-bought types, but it's also less chemical-laden.

name: Chives
description: Chives are a perennial member of the onion family that sport beautiful edible flowers.

name: Cilantro
description: Cilantro is a fast-growing, aromatic, annual herb that grows best in the cooler weather of spring and fall.

name: Corn
description: Corn is a tender annual crop that produces ears of yellow, white, or bi-colored kernels.

name: Cucumbers
description: Cucumbers grow quicly as long as they receive consistent watering and warmth.

name: Dill
description: Fragrant dill is used most commnly in soups and stews or for pickling.

name: Eggplants
description: Eggplants—also known as aubergines or brinjals.

name: Green Beans
description: Green beans are a staple because they are so easy to grow—even in limited space—and incredibly productive!

name: Jalapeño Peppers
description: Chili peppers, including jalapeños, are warm-weather vegetables which are fun to grow (and eat)!

name: Kale
description: Kale is one of the most nutritious vegetables you can grow.

name: Kohlrabi
description: Kohlrabi is a cool-season vegetable, often overlooked because of its strange appearance.

name: Lettuce
description: The fresh homegrown lettuce is far superior in both taste and vitamin A content, to the store-bought alternative.

name: Okra
description: Okra thrives in warm weather and is traditionally grown in the southern U.S.

name: Onions
description: Onions are planted early in the spring and harvested from midsummer through the fall.

name: Oregano
description: A must-have herb in a culinary garden, oregano is easy to grow and perfect for beginners.

name: Parsley
description: Parsley is a biennial plant with bright green, feather-like leaves that is in the same family as dill.

name: Parsnips
description: Parsnips enrich soups and stews but can also be enjoyed as a side dish.

name: Peas
description: Peas are one of the season’s first crops, planted as soon as the ground can be worked.

name: Potatoes
description: The taste and texture of homegrown potatoes are far superior to those of store-bought spuds!

name: Pumpkins
description: Pumpkins do not disappoint—if you have the space to grow them.

name: Radishes
description: Radishes are hardy root vegetables grown for their crisp, colorful and peppery roots.

name: Rosemary
description: Rosemary is a perennial evergreen shrub with blue flowers. It’s an aromatic and distinctive herb.

name: Sage
description: Garden sage is easy to grow—and a wonderful culinary herb that flavors meat and bean dishes

name: Spinach
description: Spinach is a popular crop that can be planted in very early spring, as well as in fall and even winter in some areas.

name: Sweet Potatoes
description: Sweet potato plants can produce a generous harvest of this nutritious, sweet-tasting root vegetable.

name: Swiss Chard
description: Chards are high in vitamins A, C, and K, as well as minerals, phytonutrients, and fiber.

name: Thyme
description: Thyme is a wonderful herb with a pleasant, pungent, clover flavor.

name: Tomatoes
description: Tomato plants are tender warm-season crops that love the sun and cannot bear frost.

name: Turnips
description: Turnips are cool-weather vegetables that can be grown both in spring and fall.

name: Watermelons
description: Native to Africa, melons require warm temperatures and a long growing season.

name: Winter Squash
description: Growing winter squash requires some patience, but worth the wait with long shelf life.

name: Zucchini
description: Zucchini is known to be staggeringly productive. Erin's Fav!
